  "text": "and characterization of simple renal cysts and solid neoplasms [CITATION_1] . The presence or absence of enhancement within a renal mass is the most important factor in its proper characterization. When a predominant part of a renal mass enhances, the mass is considered solid and likely neoplastic. Otherwise, it is important to be aware of the possibility of pseudoenhancement and to know when to suspect it. All solid lesions demonstrated gadolinium enhancement, not only RCC and invasive transitional cell carcinomas but also oncocytomas and AML (see Figures 12 and 14) . Although enhancement is sufficient for predicting malignancy, nonenhancement is not sufficient to exclude malignancy, and again the integration of T2 appearance is useful in improving the differentiation between benign from malignant renal lesions [CITATION_2] .",
